Trait wiwi::memory_usage::Dynamic

source Â· 
pub trait Dynamic {
    // Required method
    fn calculate_memory_usage(&self) -> usize;

    // Provided method
    fn calculate_values_usage(&self) -> usize { ... }
}
Available on crate feature memory-usage-unstable only.
Expand description

Trait implemented by types that at compile time, for whatever reason, donâ€™t have a known, fixed memory usage, but can still calculate it at runtime.

For example, Vec<u8> isnâ€™t just 24 bytes (12 bytes on 32 bit), like what Rustâ€™s size_of function would sayâ€¦ it stores elements on the heap, right? Thatâ€™s what this trait is for, and how it differs from Rustâ€™s Sized trait. This trait is implemented by types that can calculate their current actual memory usage, and not just stack usage. That is how this differs from Rustâ€™s Sized trait.

There is a blanket implementation of this trait for all types that implement Static.

Prefer to implement Static over this trait and use this trait (in eg. trait bounds) over Static where possible, for maximum flexibility.

Required MethodsÂ§

source

fn calculate_memory_usage(&self) -> usize

Calculate the memory usage of this value in bytes, including things like excess capacity, if that applies to the type of the value.

Provided MethodsÂ§

source

fn calculate_values_usage(&self) -> usize

Calculate the memory usage of the value in bytes, but only the memory thatâ€™s â€œactuallyâ€ being used.

Things like excess capacity would not be included here.

A default implementation is provided, which just calls calculate_memory_usage. You should not rely on this default implementation if your type manages excess capacity, and other similar things where there may be some memory thatâ€™s not actually used to store any data.
